<B>Introduction:  </B></font>

The application process for the Quality Leadership Institute is designed to
be a learning experience. If you want to learn more about the
characteristics of leaders, whether such characteristics are particularly
descriptive of you, and how your colleagues perceive you relative to these
characteristics, you can complete the full application process.
<P>
Of course you can also go the Leadership-Lite route - simply read the
material contained in the application. But we think you'll want at least to
see how your personal characteristics and attributes compare with those of
leaders, so don't read too far before getting out your pencil!

<P>
The Quality Schools Consortium (QSC) intends to identify, develop, inspire and support a cadre of Idaho educators who wish to lead their schools and school districts to higher levels of student learning.  We intend to do so by offering unique learning opportunities and support mechanisms to this group that address such topics as personal and organizational change, leadership, and Quality Management.  This document provides the first of such learning opportunities in the form of an application for membership in the Quality Leadership Institute (QLI).
<P>


The QSC has designed the Quality Leadership Institute around five premises. QSC believes that:<P><ul>
<B>1.</B> Leaders produce change through shared values and vision. Creative change is a leader's primary function, purpose and passion.
<p>
<B>2.</B> Leaders are neither born nor trained. Individuals learn to lead, to a considerable extent through their own life experiences.
<p>
<B>3.</B> Leaders can be neither assigned nor appointed. There is no relationship between leading and positions of authority. 
<p>
<B>4.</B> A leader does not act alone, but rather leads someone else, at a given time and  place.
<p>
<B>5.</B> Managing is a science, leading is a relationship.
The conceptual basis of the QLI and our approach to providing learning opportunities for participants stem from the works of such authors as Joel Barker, Warren Bennis, Bill Cooke, Stephen Covey, Peter Drucker, Joseph Jaworski, John Kotter, Tom Peters, Peter Senge, and Margaret Wheatley. Also included is the professional literature on Quality Management.  
<P></ul>

